\begin_layout Abstract
Social or collaborative tagging systems emerged as a novel classification
 scheme on the Web based on the collective knowledge of people.
 In sites such as 
\emph on
Del.icio.us
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Technorati
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
Flickr
\emph default
, users annotate a variety of resources, including Web pages, blogs, pictures,
 videos or bibliographic references; using freely chosen textual labels
 or tags.
 Underlying collaborative tagging systems there are ternary data structures
 known as folksonomies relating resources and users through tags, these
 information facilitate accessing and browsing of massive resource repositories.
 Collective annotations provided by people in the form of tags can also
 be exploited to organize resources on-line in a more formal classification
 scheme such as the ones provided by hierarchies or directories, alleviating
 the task of manual classification commonly required by systems such as
 directories on the Web.
 In this paper we present an empirical study carried out to determine the
 value of tags in resource classification.
 Furthermore, the use of several filtering and pre-processing operations
 to reduce the ambiguity and noise in tags are analyzed to determine whether
 they allow to increase the quality of resource classification.
\end_layout

