\begin_layout Subsection
Stemming
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In most languages, words have many morphological variants with similar semantic
 interpretations which can be treated as equivalents for information retrieval,
 as opposed to linguistic applications.
 For example, the words 
\emph on
computer
\emph default
, 
\emph on
computers
\emph default
, 
\emph on
compute
\emph default
, 
\emph on
computes
\emph default
, 
\emph on
computed
\emph default
, 
\emph on
computational
\emph default
, 
\emph on
computationally
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
computable
\emph default
 would be reduced to the single word stem 
\emph on
comput
\emph default
.
 Thus, the dimensionality of the feature space can be reduced by mapping
 morphologically similar words onto their word stem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This task is performed by stemming or conflation algorithms which are defined
 as processes of linguistic normalization in which morphological variants
 of words are reduced to their root form, called stem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "porter80algorithm"

